1
00:00:08,125 --> 00:00:11,250
-[rope creaking]
-[YURI grunting]

2
00:00:16,291 --> 00:00:18,333
[gasps]

3
00:00:24,583 --> 00:00:27,666
If I break the window, someone
might notice that I'm here.

4
00:00:27,750 --> 00:00:29,708
-[door opens]
-Huh?

5
00:00:29,791 --> 00:00:33,583
-Hund, you are dismissed.
-Yes, sir!

6
00:00:35,375 --> 00:00:36,833
[door closes]

7
00:00:38,375 --> 00:00:43,208
Good day to you, my dear girl.

8
00:00:43,291 --> 00:00:45,500
[YURI gasps]

9
00:00:48,583 --> 00:00:51,125
[DERRIDA] Hey, shouldn't we go
back to where Yuri disappeared?

10
00:00:51,208 --> 00:00:52,666
[VIDAUX]
No point.

11
00:00:52,750 --> 00:00:54,625
The people who kidnapped her
won't be there anymore,

12
00:00:54,708 --> 00:00:57,083
but they should make a stop
in the town of Bruque.

13
00:00:57,166 --> 00:00:59,333
It's the biggest
population center in the area.

14
00:00:59,416 --> 00:01:01,916
Is Big Sis
gonna be okay, Papa?

15
00:02:36,416 --> 00:02:38,458
♪

16
00:02:39,708 --> 00:02:41,750
[gasps]

17
00:02:43,333 --> 00:02:46,250
[VIDAUX] There are a lot of good
mechanics in this place, too.

18
00:02:49,750 --> 00:02:52,375
[GRAHAM] Full-course maintenance
would be preferable.

19
00:02:52,458 --> 00:02:54,541
[VIDAUX]
Yeah, I know.

20
00:02:54,625 --> 00:02:56,666
[DERRIDA]
This is our stop.

21
00:02:59,916 --> 00:03:01,541
[DERRIDA]
Let's split up for now.

22
00:03:01,625 --> 00:03:03,291
[VIDAUX]
This is where we need to end up.

23
00:03:03,375 --> 00:03:06,000
-We'll rendezvous in two hours.
-[DERRIDA] Got it.

24
00:03:10,875 --> 00:03:13,708
Now, let's get Graham
all fixed up.

25
00:03:15,541 --> 00:03:18,375
[engine chugging]

26
00:03:30,500 --> 00:03:32,916
Klaus? You in here?

27
00:03:35,875 --> 00:03:38,666
Vidaux, you're late.
It's just you two?

28
00:03:38,750 --> 00:03:41,000
One member of our party
went missing,

29
00:03:41,083 --> 00:03:43,000
and the other one's out
searching for her.

30
00:03:43,083 --> 00:03:45,041
Oh, is that so?

31
00:03:48,083 --> 00:03:50,583
[KLAUS]
Ouch, looks rough.

32
00:03:50,666 --> 00:03:53,125
You should really take
better care of him, you know.

33
00:03:53,208 --> 00:03:56,416
Just get to work. We don't
have time for small talk.

34
00:03:56,500 --> 00:03:58,750
Well, you're wound tight.
Good grief.

35
00:03:58,833 --> 00:04:02,583
Help yourself to some coffee,
take a load off.

36
00:04:02,666 --> 00:04:04,916
How's that sound? Okay?

37
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:06,458
Yeah!

38
00:04:08,125 --> 00:04:09,750
[DERRIDA]
She looks like this.

39
00:04:09,833 --> 00:04:13,291
-[sighs] I've never seen her.
-Look closer!

40
00:04:13,375 --> 00:04:15,375
She's supposed to be
in this city!

41
00:04:15,458 --> 00:04:18,458
Get that outta my face.
I've got work to do, man!

42
00:04:18,541 --> 00:04:21,083
♪

43
00:04:26,833 --> 00:04:28,875
♪

44
00:04:36,291 --> 00:04:39,833
[SCHMIDT] If you just tell me
where Derrida Yvain is,

45
00:04:39,916 --> 00:04:41,625
I'll let you go now.

46
00:04:41,708 --> 00:04:45,416
[YURI] Like I said, they took
off somewhere last night.

47
00:04:45,500 --> 00:04:47,291
I don't know
where they were going.

48
00:04:47,375 --> 00:04:50,916
[SCHMIDT] Leaving you,
their precious friend, behind?

49
00:04:54,708 --> 00:04:58,625
This town is the only place
they'd go, don't you think?

50
00:04:58,708 --> 00:05:03,041
-Yuri Dietrich.
-[gasps] Exactly who are you?

51
00:05:03,125 --> 00:05:05,833
[SCHMIDT]
This is a legal investigation.

52
00:05:05,916 --> 00:05:08,750
Personally, I would prefer
to get through it

53
00:05:08,833 --> 00:05:10,875
without harming a woman.

54
00:05:10,958 --> 00:05:12,541
I suppose if I'm patient,

55
00:05:12,625 --> 00:05:15,833
he might eventually
come looking for you, no?

56
00:05:15,916 --> 00:05:17,750
-He won't!
-Won't he?

57
00:05:17,833 --> 00:05:19,333
[gasps]

58
00:05:20,333 --> 00:05:22,916
What will you do
if he does come?

59
00:05:24,208 --> 00:05:27,833
All I want from him is the data
he currently possesses.

60
00:05:27,916 --> 00:05:30,250
If he hands it over
without a fuss...

61
00:05:31,458 --> 00:05:33,375
I won't do anything.

62
00:05:33,458 --> 00:05:35,208
Data?

63
00:05:35,291 --> 00:05:39,125
As you very well know,
because of the DZs,

64
00:05:39,208 --> 00:05:42,125
the war has become
quite a morass indeed. 

65
00:05:43,375 --> 00:05:46,041
[SCHMIDT] Ten years ago,
Derrida Yvain created

66
00:05:46,125 --> 00:05:48,541
a patch file
that would fix the DZ bug

67
00:05:48,625 --> 00:05:50,666
and stop them
from going haywire.

68
00:05:51,958 --> 00:05:55,125
But the executives of Rebuild,
who found that undesirable,

69
00:05:55,208 --> 00:05:57,500
decided to dispose of him.

70
00:05:57,583 --> 00:05:59,750
Derrida was presumed dead,

71
00:05:59,833 --> 00:06:02,458
and the patch file
was lost along with him.

72
00:06:03,500 --> 00:06:05,666
But just a year back,
we found evidence

73
00:06:05,750 --> 00:06:08,875
of someone accessing
the patch file's online data.

74
00:06:08,958 --> 00:06:11,708
They didn't even bother
to erase their footprints.

75
00:06:12,708 --> 00:06:14,875
At the time, all that told us

76
00:06:14,958 --> 00:06:17,583
was that the data existed
out there somewhere.

77
00:06:17,666 --> 00:06:20,625
But then we got confirmation
that Derrida was still alive.

78
00:06:20,708 --> 00:06:22,291
[breath quavers]

79
00:06:22,375 --> 00:06:27,166
The data he has, will have
a definitive effect on the war.

80
00:06:27,250 --> 00:06:29,333
Within the Union
Intelligence Bureau,

81
00:06:29,416 --> 00:06:30,958
some feel that
we should kill him

82
00:06:31,041 --> 00:06:33,125
before our enemies
can get their hands on it.

83
00:06:33,208 --> 00:06:36,625
-[YURI gasps]
-You understand?

84
00:06:36,708 --> 00:06:38,125
I do apologize.

85
00:06:38,208 --> 00:06:40,750
Your apartment needn't
have been destroyed.

86
00:06:40,833 --> 00:06:43,500
But it was my predecessor
who was so boorish,

87
00:06:43,583 --> 00:06:45,208
certainly not me.

88
00:06:45,291 --> 00:06:48,041
If I give you the data,
you won't touch him?

89
00:06:49,625 --> 00:06:51,375
But of course.

90
00:06:51,458 --> 00:06:52,791
-[door opens]
-Hmm?

91
00:06:52,875 --> 00:06:54,750
-Uh?
-[SCHMIDT] What is it?

92
00:06:57,416 --> 00:06:59,500
[whispering] Target's
whereabouts are confirmed.

93
00:06:59,583 --> 00:07:02,125
[scoffs]
It seems your Derrida

94
00:07:02,208 --> 00:07:04,666
-has entered the city.
-[gasps]

95
00:07:04,750 --> 00:07:06,791
[tool clacking]

96
00:07:07,958 --> 00:07:09,750
-[footsteps approach]
-Huh?

97
00:07:09,833 --> 00:07:12,458
-Hey! You're back!
-Sure am.

98
00:07:14,208 --> 00:07:17,166
-Klaus Baden's the name.
-Derrida. Nice to meet you.

99
00:07:17,250 --> 00:07:18,625
[MAYUKA grunts]

100
00:07:18,708 --> 00:07:21,125
Did you find out
where Big Sis ended up?

101
00:07:21,208 --> 00:07:23,291
-[DERRIDA] Uh-uh.
-Oh, no.

102
00:07:24,833 --> 00:07:26,250
[DERRIDA]
Where's your dad?

103
00:07:26,333 --> 00:07:28,583
He said he was
gonna go for a walk.

104
00:07:28,666 --> 00:07:30,708
[DERRIDA] I see.
I'm gonna take a quick break

105
00:07:30,791 --> 00:07:33,083
and then head back out
to search.

106
00:07:33,166 --> 00:07:35,375
Can I please come too?

107
00:07:36,458 --> 00:07:37,625
I, uh...

108
00:07:38,833 --> 00:07:40,916
-Huh?
-Here, have a cup.

109
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:43,166
Haste makes waste
as I always say.

110
00:07:43,250 --> 00:07:46,333
[MAYUKA] Grandpa Klaus's coffee
is the best ever!

111
00:07:46,416 --> 00:07:48,166
[DERRIDA]
Can you even drink coffee?

112
00:07:48,250 --> 00:07:51,083
[MAYUKA] I don't have
to drink it to know!

113
00:07:51,166 --> 00:07:52,875
Well, let's try it.

114
00:07:57,208 --> 00:07:58,500
Oh, wow!

115
00:07:58,583 --> 00:08:01,000
Grandpa Klaus is amazing
when it comes to coffee,

116
00:08:01,083 --> 00:08:02,583
and cars too!

117
00:08:02,666 --> 00:08:04,625
The only reason we have
Graham the way he is,

118
00:08:04,708 --> 00:08:07,333
is ‘cause Grandpa
modified him over and over!

119
00:08:07,416 --> 00:08:09,625
Well, it's not all that.

120
00:08:09,708 --> 00:08:12,000
I just do what I love,
know what I mean?

121
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:20,625
[DERRIDA]
Thank you for the coffee.

122
00:08:20,708 --> 00:08:24,041
-[VIDAUX] Where are you going?
-Where else? To look for Yuri!

123
00:08:24,125 --> 00:08:26,541
Have you accomplished
anything wandering around?

124
00:08:26,625 --> 00:08:29,833
-Not yet.
-Hmm. I'm getting a cup.

125
00:08:29,916 --> 00:08:31,541
-Good?
-[KLAUS] Sure.

126
00:08:31,625 --> 00:08:33,083
Huh?

127
00:08:33,166 --> 00:08:36,000
[VIDAUX] Unlike you,
I managed to turn something up.

128
00:08:37,458 --> 00:08:39,208
Some official
named Schmidt Maier

129
00:08:39,291 --> 00:08:41,833
is asking around
about you out there.

130
00:08:47,625 --> 00:08:50,166
Apparently, he turned up
a couple of days ago.

131
00:08:50,250 --> 00:08:53,041
Went around the city
showing people a picture of you.

132
00:08:54,583 --> 00:08:56,625
♪

133
00:09:07,625 --> 00:09:09,166
They say he was
with a young woman

134
00:09:09,250 --> 00:09:11,208
who appeared to be
in some distress.

135
00:09:11,291 --> 00:09:14,208
So you know where he is now?
We have to go and save Yuri!

136
00:09:14,291 --> 00:09:15,833
If you're the one
they're really after,

137
00:09:15,916 --> 00:09:17,916
they'll use Yuri as a hostage.

138
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,000
We can't make a move just yet.

139
00:09:20,083 --> 00:09:23,458
-So what should we do then?
-We wait for them to act first.

140
00:09:23,541 --> 00:09:25,416
Just sit around?

141
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:28,166
It's all we can do. You think
we're not worried about her too?

142
00:09:28,250 --> 00:09:31,625
Oh... I'm sorry.

143
00:09:32,958 --> 00:09:35,000
I heard another
unsettling rumor out there.

144
00:09:35,083 --> 00:09:36,333
Hmm?

145
00:09:36,416 --> 00:09:38,500
It's been years now
since the haywire DZs

146
00:09:38,583 --> 00:09:40,791
were unleashed into the streets.

147
00:09:40,875 --> 00:09:43,708
But despite the continued chaos
and the increase in victims,

148
00:09:43,791 --> 00:09:47,250
the government's promised recall
plan still hasn't gone anywhere.

149
00:09:47,333 --> 00:09:49,250
Rather than making it
right like they promised,

150
00:09:49,333 --> 00:09:50,833
they're planning to wipe
the slate clean

151
00:09:50,916 --> 00:09:53,750
of their irresponsible conduct
by dropping missiles.

152
00:09:53,833 --> 00:09:55,666
-That's absurd!
-We live in a world

153
00:09:55,750 --> 00:09:58,458
where the craziest thing
is the most likely to be true.

154
00:09:58,541 --> 00:10:00,625
It's not even funny anymore.

155
00:10:00,708 --> 00:10:04,666
War always serves well
to rob men of their right minds.

156
00:10:04,750 --> 00:10:07,208
And imagine if that triggers
a retaliation system

157
00:10:07,291 --> 00:10:10,541
that was set in place
for missile attacks. What then?

158
00:10:10,625 --> 00:10:13,125
Two countries destroyed
at the same time.

159
00:10:13,208 --> 00:10:15,666
At this point, I think
I could leave this world

160
00:10:15,750 --> 00:10:18,000
without any regrets.

161
00:10:18,083 --> 00:10:19,791
All I'd really want,

162
00:10:19,875 --> 00:10:22,958
is for someone to remember me
after I bit the dust.

163
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:28,541
But then, if that person
didn't have a future

164
00:10:28,625 --> 00:10:30,875
to spend with those memories...

165
00:10:30,958 --> 00:10:32,333
[DERRIDA]
Wha...?

166
00:10:32,416 --> 00:10:34,833
[birds twittering]

167
00:10:35,791 --> 00:10:37,041
Huh?

168
00:10:37,125 --> 00:10:38,625
[squeals]

169
00:10:39,875 --> 00:10:43,041
I won't allow it.
Can't let that happen.

170
00:10:49,791 --> 00:10:50,958
[gasps softly]

171
00:10:53,958 --> 00:10:56,000
[breath quavers]

172
00:10:56,958 --> 00:10:59,375
[FEMALE NARRATOR]
Clockwise. Anti-clockwise.

173
00:11:03,166 --> 00:11:04,833
[MAN]
It's regrettable,

174
00:11:04,916 --> 00:11:07,166
but we've done
everything we can.

175
00:11:07,250 --> 00:11:10,250
[MAN 2] There's no other way
to retrieve them.

176
00:11:10,333 --> 00:11:13,041
[MAN 3] It's an appropriate
decision, I believe.

177
00:11:17,958 --> 00:11:19,833
[VIDAUX]
Derrida.

178
00:11:19,916 --> 00:11:23,208
-Hey. Are listening to me?
-Huh?

179
00:11:23,291 --> 00:11:25,250
I was saying that I heard
a government official

180
00:11:25,333 --> 00:11:27,416
blocked off the bridges
last night.

181
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:30,583
They're probably attempting
to trap us inside the city.

182
00:11:30,666 --> 00:11:33,416
Their next move will likely
be making contact with you.

183
00:11:33,500 --> 00:11:35,708
I see.

184
00:11:37,458 --> 00:11:40,000
[VIDAUX] Better start
getting yourself together.

185
00:11:42,166 --> 00:11:45,041
-We'll head back first.
-[MAYUKA] I'm ready to go, Papa!

186
00:11:45,125 --> 00:11:46,750
[DERRIDA]
Sure. I'll stick around,

187
00:11:46,833 --> 00:11:48,875
try to gather some more info.

188
00:11:49,916 --> 00:11:52,958
♪

189
00:11:53,041 --> 00:11:54,833
-[SCHMIDT] Derrida Yvain.
-Huh?

190
00:11:54,916 --> 00:11:56,791
[SCHMIDT] Don't turn around.
Just hear me out.

191
00:11:58,333 --> 00:12:00,458
I promise I'll keep this brief.

192
00:12:00,541 --> 00:12:02,791
My name is Schmidt Maier.

193
00:12:02,875 --> 00:12:05,333
We have Yuri Dietrich
in our possession.

194
00:12:05,416 --> 00:12:07,125
My proposal is simple:

195
00:12:07,208 --> 00:12:09,791
I wish to trade her
for the DZ patch file

196
00:12:09,875 --> 00:12:14,125
-that you created.
-I see. Is she safe?

197
00:12:14,208 --> 00:12:16,458
Please,
I'm a government bureaucrat.

198
00:12:16,541 --> 00:12:18,916
It's true that I have
forcibly taken her into custody

199
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,166
to facilitate
our little trade.

200
00:12:21,250 --> 00:12:24,125
But I'd never resort
to more unsightly behavior.

201
00:12:24,208 --> 00:12:26,208
And what will you do
with the patch file?

202
00:12:26,291 --> 00:12:29,541
Well, you see, my job ends
once I retrieve the thing.

203
00:12:29,625 --> 00:12:33,708
How it's then utilized is up
to those in other departments.

204
00:12:33,791 --> 00:12:36,666
I've heard some rumors about
a large-scale missile attack.

205
00:12:37,750 --> 00:12:40,416
-[SCHMIDT] Haven't the foggiest.
-Don't play dumb.

206
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:43,375
If you're really in the
government, then you must know.

207
00:12:43,458 --> 00:12:45,958
[SCHMIDT] And what if the rumors
do turn out to be true?

208
00:12:46,041 --> 00:12:48,583
That's simple.
Offer to use the patch file

209
00:12:48,666 --> 00:12:51,625
to restore control of the DZs
and negotiate a ceasefire.

210
00:12:51,708 --> 00:12:53,250
[gasps quietly]

211
00:12:53,333 --> 00:12:55,916
If you could do that,
I'll gladly give it to you.

212
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,750
[scoffs]

213
00:12:57,833 --> 00:13:01,500
The Trout Theory.
That's what you called it, yes?

214
00:13:01,583 --> 00:13:04,291
The thesis you presented
in your student days.

215
00:13:04,375 --> 00:13:06,666
Your present consciousness
traveling back in time

216
00:13:06,750 --> 00:13:08,375
to your former body.

217
00:13:08,458 --> 00:13:10,875
-An interesting concept.
-How did you know?

218
00:13:10,958 --> 00:13:13,833
Basic research into my
target's government files.

219
00:13:13,916 --> 00:13:16,000
You're a dreamer, Mr. Yvain.

220
00:13:16,083 --> 00:13:18,375
A man with lofty ideals.

221
00:13:19,708 --> 00:13:21,291
I'll be frank.

222
00:13:21,375 --> 00:13:24,875
I don't have the authority
to accept your proposal.

223
00:13:24,958 --> 00:13:27,541
And besides,
it's not as if a single file

224
00:13:27,625 --> 00:13:30,541
could really save the world
we find ourselves in.

225
00:13:31,958 --> 00:13:33,916
[SCHMIDT]
Listen to me.

226
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:35,416
The world is the end result

227
00:13:35,500 --> 00:13:39,625
of a series of decisions
and actions, nothing more.

228
00:13:39,708 --> 00:13:43,541
Just as its always been.
No dream can change that.

229
00:13:43,625 --> 00:13:47,833
Even if you feel that your dream
is right and the world is wrong.

230
00:13:47,916 --> 00:13:51,875
Tonight, at nine PM, come
to the bridge with the file.

231
00:13:51,958 --> 00:13:55,333
Bring your friend,
the Destruct, with you.

232
00:13:55,416 --> 00:13:57,166
Unarmed, all right?

233
00:13:58,416 --> 00:14:00,333
[DERRIDA]
Hmm.

234
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,708
Uh?
Derrida, welcome back!

235
00:14:07,791 --> 00:14:09,625
[VIDAUX]
How did your meeting go?

236
00:14:09,708 --> 00:14:12,583
What did you...?
You knew that he was there?

237
00:14:12,666 --> 00:14:15,250
Figured I would let you boys
have a private chat.

238
00:14:17,500 --> 00:14:20,708
[DERRIDA]
He's after the DZ patch file.

239
00:14:20,791 --> 00:14:24,500
Tonight, at nine PM,
he wants to trade Yuri for it.

240
00:14:24,583 --> 00:14:28,291
-And he said to bring you.
-I get an invitation, too?

241
00:14:28,375 --> 00:14:30,625
[scoffs]
I'm honored.

242
00:14:30,708 --> 00:14:32,333
But you don't even
have the data,

243
00:14:32,416 --> 00:14:34,333
-so then...
-They don't know that.

244
00:14:34,416 --> 00:14:36,333
They seem to think I have
the patch file on me,

245
00:14:36,416 --> 00:14:38,750
for some reason.
To be safe,

246
00:14:38,833 --> 00:14:40,333
I guess I'll bring
an empty memory card.

247
00:14:40,416 --> 00:14:43,166
But they're going to want
to check the contents on-site,

248
00:14:43,250 --> 00:14:45,625
-you've gotta know that.
-Huh?

249
00:14:49,166 --> 00:14:52,875
No second-guessing yourself.
It's time to take action.

250
00:14:52,958 --> 00:14:55,250
-Ready?
-Huh?

251
00:14:55,333 --> 00:14:57,375
Of course.

252
00:15:16,875 --> 00:15:18,041
Derrida!

253
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:23,791
[SCHMIDT]
Stop right there, gentlemen.

254
00:15:23,875 --> 00:15:26,083
No weapons as promised,
I trust.

255
00:15:26,166 --> 00:15:28,083
[VIDAUX]
Yeah, totally unarmed.

256
00:15:28,166 --> 00:15:29,833
Also, if I catch
a cold out here,

257
00:15:29,916 --> 00:15:31,625
I'm forwarding you
my medical bills.

258
00:15:31,708 --> 00:15:34,083
I believe that's
quite enough chit-chat.

259
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:36,125
The file.

260
00:15:37,541 --> 00:15:39,708
Now hand it over.

261
00:15:39,791 --> 00:15:42,416
[DERRIDA] First,
I want to ask you a favor.

262
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:44,541
[SCHMIDT] If you think you're in
a position to set conditions--

263
00:15:44,625 --> 00:15:47,750
This is a government-sanctioned
exchange, right, Mr. Maier?

264
00:15:47,833 --> 00:15:49,166
Then logic dictates

265
00:15:49,250 --> 00:15:51,166
that there should be
an official record of it.

266
00:15:51,250 --> 00:15:53,583
-[SCHMIDT] Does it now.
-What are you...?

267
00:15:53,666 --> 00:15:56,333
I would like photographic
evidence of our meeting.

268
00:15:56,416 --> 00:15:58,500
You're a government man,
you should recognize

269
00:15:58,583 --> 00:16:01,208
the importance
of keeping a record.

270
00:16:01,291 --> 00:16:04,291
You brat.
You think this is a joke?

271
00:16:04,375 --> 00:16:06,541
Take care of him!

272
00:16:06,625 --> 00:16:08,916
-Look out!
-[grunts]

273
00:16:12,333 --> 00:16:14,708
-[KLAUS] That's the signal.
-[MAYUKA] Right.

274
00:16:14,791 --> 00:16:16,625
[shouts]

275
00:16:16,708 --> 00:16:19,500
-[grunts, coughs]
-[explosion]

276
00:16:21,291 --> 00:16:24,166
Do you really think
this is going to work? [coughs]

277
00:16:24,250 --> 00:16:25,916
-[grunts]
-Aah!

278
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:27,666
Damn you, let go!

279
00:16:27,750 --> 00:16:32,125
-Barbaric girl!
-Yuri! I've got you, okay?

280
00:16:33,625 --> 00:16:36,500
-Run for it, now!
-This way!

281
00:16:38,916 --> 00:16:40,916
-Over here!
-[panting]

282
00:16:42,250 --> 00:16:45,041
-Now, to the garage?
-[VIDAUX] It's all set.

283
00:16:47,708 --> 00:16:50,000
Pursue in the Canopies!

284
00:16:50,083 --> 00:16:51,875
-Roger!
-Roger!

285
00:16:51,958 --> 00:16:55,208
Little fools.
I'll teach them a lesson!

286
00:16:55,291 --> 00:16:57,333
That was really close.

287
00:16:57,416 --> 00:16:59,416
I was so worried. They said
they planned on killing you

288
00:16:59,500 --> 00:17:01,541
the moment you handed
over the data to them.

289
00:17:01,625 --> 00:17:05,333
-Yeah, I figured.
-[VIDAUX] We're almost there.

290
00:17:09,833 --> 00:17:11,166
[KLAUS]
Very well done!

291
00:17:11,250 --> 00:17:13,208
[MAYUKA]
That smoke screen was so cool!

292
00:17:13,291 --> 00:17:15,500
Wait! You brought her
with you, old man?

293
00:17:15,583 --> 00:17:18,291
Are you suggesting I should have
left her here all alone?

294
00:17:18,375 --> 00:17:21,833
Graham's done, by the way.
You're welcome. Now go.

295
00:17:21,916 --> 00:17:24,833
Uh... Fine, thank you.

296
00:17:24,916 --> 00:17:27,125
[DERRIDA]
We're really grateful.

297
00:17:27,208 --> 00:17:29,791
-[YURI] Thank you so much, sir.
-[KLAUS] No problem, kids.

298
00:17:29,875 --> 00:17:32,583
-See you later, Grandpa!
-You better be drinking coffee

299
00:17:32,666 --> 00:17:34,708
by the next time
I see you, okay?

300
00:17:34,791 --> 00:17:37,791
-Um, yeah, sure.
-Take care, Vidaux.

301
00:17:37,875 --> 00:17:40,000
Quit giving Graham
such a hard time.

302
00:17:40,083 --> 00:17:42,541
And don't go getting
yourselves killed.

303
00:17:42,625 --> 00:17:44,375
We're heading out.

304
00:17:48,125 --> 00:17:51,333
[engines roaring]

305
00:17:55,208 --> 00:17:57,875
-[KATZE] Target sighted.
-Open fire!

306
00:17:57,958 --> 00:18:00,791
Use whatever force necessary
to retrieve that file!

307
00:18:08,458 --> 00:18:11,916
[GRAHAM] A recovering patient
should not be subjected to this.

308
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:15,708
Don't be such a crybaby.
Okay, hang on tight everybody.

309
00:18:15,791 --> 00:18:18,666
[tires screeching]

310
00:18:22,208 --> 00:18:24,750
[KATZE over radio] Target is
heading for the bridge.

311
00:18:24,833 --> 00:18:26,583
[scoffs]
What idiots.

312
00:18:27,791 --> 00:18:30,000
I see my duties through
without fail!

313
00:18:31,916 --> 00:18:35,833
-[explosion]
-[crumbling]

314
00:18:35,916 --> 00:18:38,625
-Oh no!
-[VIDAUX] I knew it.

315
00:18:38,708 --> 00:18:41,000
[DERRIDA] Is that basket case
really with the government?

316
00:18:43,166 --> 00:18:44,916
How very sad.

317
00:18:48,833 --> 00:18:50,541
We're still heading
straight for it!

318
00:18:50,625 --> 00:18:52,833
[GRAHAM]
There is no need for concern.

319
00:18:52,916 --> 00:18:55,291
Prepare for impact!
Let's go!

320
00:18:56,666 --> 00:18:59,500
[KATZE] Target is accelerating.
They haven't changed trajectory!

321
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:03,833
There's no way!
That can't be.

322
00:19:14,250 --> 00:19:16,041
[screaming]

323
00:19:24,458 --> 00:19:26,541
-What the--?
-Unreal!

324
00:19:26,625 --> 00:19:28,208
[GRAHAM] I will take that
as a compliment.

325
00:19:28,291 --> 00:19:30,333
Come on.
This is all the old man!

326
00:19:30,416 --> 00:19:31,875
Yeah, for sure!

327
00:19:31,958 --> 00:19:34,208
Like I told you, he's a genius
with coffee and cars!

328
00:19:34,291 --> 00:19:36,791
You still haven't tasted
the coffee!

329
00:19:36,875 --> 00:19:39,041
[KATZE] They're driving
across the water, sir!

330
00:19:39,125 --> 00:19:42,541
[SCHMIDT over radio] Don't let
them get away! Fire, now! Do it!

331
00:19:50,375 --> 00:19:51,791
[GRAHAM] Missiles approaching
from behind.

332
00:19:51,875 --> 00:19:53,666
[VIDAUX]
I know, damn it!

333
00:19:56,083 --> 00:19:58,041
[explosion]

334
00:19:58,125 --> 00:20:00,750
-Those things are no joke!
-Playtime's over.

335
00:20:00,833 --> 00:20:02,875
[rapid firing]

336
00:20:10,791 --> 00:20:12,666
[men grunting]

337
00:20:12,750 --> 00:20:14,875
[KATZE]
Target... lost.

338
00:20:16,750 --> 00:20:19,125
[growls]
No.

339
00:20:26,916 --> 00:20:29,708
Looks like...
we're finally in the clear.

340
00:20:29,791 --> 00:20:33,541
-I'm glad you're safe.
-Sorry for worrying you.

341
00:20:33,625 --> 00:20:35,791
[DERRIDA] Why did you go off
on your own, anyway?

342
00:20:35,875 --> 00:20:39,625
[YURI] First, there's something
I need to tell you, Derrida.

343
00:20:39,708 --> 00:20:41,166
-Huh?
-Huh?

344
00:20:42,208 --> 00:20:44,458
The reason that Mage
went missing...

345
00:20:45,833 --> 00:20:49,250
was because of me.

346
00:20:51,125 --> 00:20:54,375
I was cleaning, and I found it.

347
00:20:54,458 --> 00:20:56,833
I used the access key
and it ruined everything.

348
00:20:58,750 --> 00:21:01,041
It's my fault
Mage had to run away.

349
00:21:01,125 --> 00:21:02,500
I lied to you.

350
00:21:02,583 --> 00:21:04,500
After a while,
I wanted to tell you the truth,

351
00:21:04,583 --> 00:21:06,916
but I didn't know how.

352
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:11,208
-It's not your fault.
-No! It is!

353
00:21:11,291 --> 00:21:13,708
-And, um, also...
-Huh?

354
00:21:13,791 --> 00:21:15,833
Mage, she still...

355
00:21:17,666 --> 00:21:19,500
She still really cares
about you.

356
00:21:19,583 --> 00:21:21,041
What?

357
00:21:21,125 --> 00:21:22,541
The thing is,
she's loved you ever

358
00:21:22,625 --> 00:21:24,708
since she was a little girl.

359
00:21:24,791 --> 00:21:27,458
And those feelings haven't
changed after all these years.

360
00:21:27,541 --> 00:21:33,375
So, Derrida,
promise me you'll find Mage!

361
00:21:34,875 --> 00:21:36,583
I promise.

362
00:21:39,791 --> 00:21:42,958
♪

363
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:23,708
[CASSIEL] You're going to do
this by yourself?

364
00:23:23,791 --> 00:23:26,750
What about Derrida?
Are you sure?

365
00:23:26,833 --> 00:23:29,500
Mm. Yes, I'm sure.

366
00:23:29,583 --> 00:23:34,208
Derrida, if he knew what I was
about to do, he'd be against it.

367
00:23:34,291 --> 00:23:36,666
This is something I have
to finish by myself,

368
00:23:36,750 --> 00:23:38,875
without anyone's help.

